---
import GuideLayout from '../components/layout/GuideLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DataTable from '../components/ui/DataTable.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/seo/JsonLd.astro';

const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: 'danger-zones', text: 'Danger Zones' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'gold-escrow', text: 'Gold Escrow' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'initiating-pvp', text: 'Initiating PvP' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'fleeing', text: 'Fleeing' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'rewards-and-penalties', text: 'Rewards and Penalties' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'group-pvp', text: 'Group PvP' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'pvp-strategy', text: 'PvP Strategy' },
];
---

<GuideLayout
  title="Blood in the Dark"
  description="PvP guide for Ultimate Dominion. Danger zones, gold escrow mechanics, flee penalties, combat rewards, and player-vs-player strategy."
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'PvP' }]}
  headings={headings}
>
  <JsonLd schema={{
    '@type': 'Article',
    headline: 'Blood in the Dark — Ultimate Dominion PvP Guide',
    description: 'How player-vs-player combat works in Ultimate Dominion: danger zones, gold escrow, flee penalties, and strategic advice.',
    dateModified: '2026-03-27',
  }} slot="head" />

  <h1>Blood in the Dark</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-text-secondary">
    Ultimate Dominion features player-vs-player combat in designated danger zones. The winner claims 40% of the loser's wallet gold (10% burned, 40% to winner). PvP uses the same turn-based combat system as PvE, with a 30-second cooldown between encounters. The safe zone (northwest 5x5 corner) has PvP disabled; everything else is the danger zone.
  </p>
  <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary/60 mt-2">Last updated: March 2026</p>

  <h2 id="danger-zones">Danger Zones</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Northwest 5x5 is safe (PvP disabled). Everything outside is the danger zone with PvP enabled and tougher monsters.</em></p>
  <p>
    The world map is divided into <strong>safe zones</strong> and <strong>danger zones</strong>:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Safe zone</strong> — the 5&times;5 northwest corner of the map, near the cave entrance. PvP is disabled here. Only monsters can attack you.</li>
    <li><strong>Danger zone</strong> — everything outside the safe corner. Both PvE and PvP are active. Any player on the same tile can attack you.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout type="warning" title="Entering the danger zone is a choice">
    The danger zone contains tougher monsters with better drops — but also other players who may be hunting for your gold. The higher rewards come with real risk.
  </Callout>

  <p>
    The <a href="/guide/dark-cave">Dark Cave map</a> shows exactly which tiles are safe and which are dangerous.
  </p>

  <h2 id="gold-escrow">Gold Escrow</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Deposit gold at the cave entrance before entering danger zones. Only escrowed gold is at risk — main balance is always safe.</em></p>
  <p>
    Before entering the danger zone, you must deposit gold into <strong>Adventure Escrow</strong> at the cave entrance tile. This gold is what's at stake in PvP:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Only escrowed gold can be lost or won in PvP — gold in your main balance is always safe.</li>
    <li>You can deposit or withdraw at the entrance at any time.</li>
    <li>You need escrowed gold to participate in PvP combat.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="initiating-pvp">Initiating PvP</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Same tile + danger zone required. 30-second cooldown between fights. Standard combat rules apply.</em></p>
  <p>
    To attack another player, you must be on the same tile in a danger zone. Select the player and choose to attack. Rules:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>There is a <strong>30-second cooldown</strong> between PvP encounters.</li>
    <li>The faster combatant (higher total AGI) acts first.</li>
    <li>Standard <a href="/guide/combat">combat rules</a> apply — same hit formulas, damage calculations, combat triangle, and turn limits.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="fleeing">Fleeing</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>10% wallet gold penalty to flee — 5% to opponent, 5% burned. Attacker flees turn 1, defender turn 2.</em></p>
  <p>
    Either side can attempt to flee, but it comes at a cost:
  </p>

  <DataTable headers={['Who', 'Can Flee On', 'Penalty']}>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50">
      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">Attacker</td>
      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">Turn 1</td>
      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-red">10% of wallet gold</td>
    </tr>
    <tr class="hover:bg-surface/50">
      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">Defender</td>
      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">Turn 2</td>
      <td class="px-4 py-3 text-red">10% of wallet gold</td>
    </tr>
  </DataTable>

  <p>
    The flee penalty is <strong>10% of your wallet gold</strong>. 5% goes to the other player, 5% is burned (removed from the economy). This discourages hit-and-run tactics while still giving an escape route when you're outmatched. The Smoke Cloak effect (from Flashpowder) negates the flee penalty.
  </p>

  <Callout type="info" title="PvE flee penalty">
    Fleeing from monsters (PvE) costs <strong>5% of your wallet gold</strong>, burned entirely. Lower risk than PvP, but still not free.
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="tip" title="Know when to run">
    If you're clearly outmatched — wrong side of the combat triangle, lower level, worse gear — fleeing on your first available turn and losing 10% is often better than fighting and losing 50%.
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="rewards-and-penalties">Rewards and Penalties</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Loser loses 50% of wallet gold — 40% to winner, 10% burned. Draws have no consequences.</em></p>
  <p>
    When PvP combat ends decisively:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Loser</strong> loses <strong>50%</strong> of their wallet gold.</li>
    <li><strong>Winner</strong> receives <strong>40%</strong> of the loser's wallet gold.</li>
    <li><strong>10%</strong> of the loser's wallet gold is <strong>burned</strong> (permanent gold sink).</li>
    <li>If the fight draws (15-turn limit), neither side gains or loses.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="group-pvp">Group PvP</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><em>Always 1v1 — select a single target. Other players on the tile are unaffected.</em></p>
  <p>
    Multiple players can occupy the same tile. In group scenarios:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>PvP is always <strong>1v1</strong> — you select a single target.</li>
    <li>Other players on the tile are not affected by your fight.</li>
    <li>After your fight ends, you can engage another opponent (after the 30-second cooldown).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="pvp-strategy">PvP Strategy</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Know the triangle</strong> — check your opponent's stats or class before attacking. A Warrior attacking a Mage is walking into a disadvantage.</li>
    <li><strong>Control your escrow</strong> — only bring what you're willing to risk. Deposit small amounts while learning.</li>
    <li><strong>Consumables matter</strong> — a well-timed <a href="/guide/items">Smoke Bomb</a> or stat buff can swing a close fight.</li>
    <li><strong>Positioning</strong> — if you see a dangerous player on a tile, go around. The cave has multiple paths.</li>
    <li><strong>Class abilities</strong> — <a href="/guide/classes">Rogue's Shadowstep</a> and Warlock's Soul Drain are particularly strong in PvP due to burst and debuffs.</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout type="lore">
    The old rules died with the gods. In the deep dark, there is no law but what you carry in your sword hand. Every adventurer knows the risk. Some come for the gold. Others come for the sport.
  </Callout>
</GuideLayout>
